1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,487
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:09,176 --> 00:00:31,611
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:38,661
The

4
00:00:40,447 --> 00:01:09,102
meditation that we do this vipassana puts us into a sort of peculiar position with ourselves because having found this position within ourselves we sort of abstract from everything that we would normally call ourselves everything becomes an object something to observe

5
00:01:12,204 --> 00:01:23,515
somehow we have to re-enter that psycho-physical organism and sort of wander about the world.

6
00:01:24,980 --> 00:01:35,216
Sometimes we mistake that meditation in day life thinking that we have to be self-aware to try and keep this sort of distance within ourselves.

7
00:01:36,459 --> 00:01:39,203
Well, that of course creates quite a split.

8
00:01:40,426 --> 00:01:50,042
And although self-awareness does arise at times, even if it arises in not such a skillful way, such as when we're embarrassed,

9
00:01:50,865 --> 00:01:52,987
You become very self-aware.

10
00:01:53,007 --> 00:01:57,173
But the fact that it arises sometimes is not a problem.

11
00:01:58,254 --> 00:02:05,641
But if we make that, if we think that that's the way we ought to be, then it does become a problem because there's a split.

12
00:02:06,763 --> 00:02:09,045
There's me trying to watch myself trying to do something.

13
00:02:09,667 --> 00:02:13,770
It's just, you can't do it if you haven't got bills anyway.

14
00:02:13,971 --> 00:02:16,653
Try reading, watching yourself read.

15
00:02:16,674 --> 00:02:17,275
You can't do it.

16
00:02:18,216 --> 00:02:20,838
So we have to re-engage

17
00:02:22,169 --> 00:02:34,997
Now what we come to recognize within ourselves is that a lot of the things that we do are coming from wrong attitudes.

18
00:02:36,039 --> 00:02:57,491
So, you know, in the classic teaching it's all to do with greed, with acquisitiveness, all to do with aversion and fear, anxiety, both, you know, that sort of aversion of pushing away and the aversion of running away.

19
00:02:59,782 --> 00:03:08,954
So, knowing that, it's important before we begin an action to actually be quite clear about our attitude.

20
00:03:10,675 --> 00:03:16,302
And in the Eightfold Path, remember, this right understanding is first, is what we get through the meditation.

21
00:03:17,264 --> 00:03:21,209
And it drops into a right attitude, into a heart state.

22
00:03:22,890 --> 00:03:27,276
So that attitude, remember, is not an emotional state, it's where you put your wills.

23
00:03:28,454 --> 00:03:40,657
why are you doing what you're doing so being very clear about that when you enter into the action then we're producing good conditionings within ourselves

24
00:03:46,324 --> 00:03:56,919
just on a very simple level, if you say that you'll help somebody, you see, you might be in a habit of just saying yes.

25
00:03:57,600 --> 00:03:58,502
You know, will you do this?

26
00:03:58,543 --> 00:03:58,782
Yes.

27
00:03:59,563 --> 00:04:02,008
And then after you've said it, you say to yourself, what did I say that for?

28
00:04:02,908 --> 00:04:04,211
I don't want to do that.

29
00:04:04,230 --> 00:04:05,772
And you get quite negative about it.

30
00:04:06,354 --> 00:04:08,037
And you do it, but there's a grudge there.

31
00:04:10,020 --> 00:04:15,807
So what was meant to be a very beautiful thing, a very happy thing to do, turns into something quite

32
00:04:16,783 --> 00:04:30,927
painful now if you have stopped you see it and then actually made that as a point of reflection and then said yes i'll help then that comes from a right attitude and then you get the gift of happiness from it

33
00:04:36,206 --> 00:04:46,718
So that ability to make the right intention, in order to do that, we've got to get in the habit of stopping, of actually just a moment of reflection.

34
00:04:48,660 --> 00:04:52,725
And that's one of the very skillful habits that we can get into.

35
00:04:52,764 --> 00:05:00,492
So when you've finished an action, no matter what it is, and there's a stop,

36
00:05:02,194 --> 00:05:30,142
and the next intention comes and you can see that intention if you don't stop then you're in that sort of rush mode so if you look at the Eightfold Path you see it begins with this right understanding we form an intention from it which is the right attitude and then that affects the way we speak

37
00:05:31,473 --> 00:05:40,807
what we do, and our livelihood, how we're actually making a living.

38
00:05:53,377 --> 00:06:00,987
Now the two main attitudes or the two main positions that we have to take is this sense of attention.

39
00:06:02,149 --> 00:06:06,036
Sense of putting our attention where we want to put it.

40
00:06:07,096 --> 00:06:08,358
And the other one is care.

41
00:06:08,660 --> 00:06:09,880
That's where we put the heart.

42
00:06:10,521 --> 00:06:17,713
So these two things, attention and care, are the sort of guiding modes that we need for everything we do.

43
00:06:18,487 --> 00:06:30,286
So, to get that attention right, it's a case of putting ourselves into the action, a sort of full engagement in what we're doing.

44
00:06:32,610 --> 00:06:37,660
Now, it's at those points that we see that sense of self-awareness disappears.

45
00:06:38,567 --> 00:06:51,963
And if it comes with care as well, then the heart's behind it, and you find that that movement into a loss of self-awareness into what you're doing comes with ease.

46
00:06:53,124 --> 00:06:55,827
Now it happens to us naturally when we're doing something we love to do.

47
00:06:56,088 --> 00:07:06,819
I mean, if you're a gardener, for instance, you might finish something, and when you look back at the action, you can see that it's done beautifully, it's done well.

48
00:07:08,656 --> 00:07:10,577
But there's been not a sense of time.

49
00:07:10,617 --> 00:07:12,860
There's been no sense of time.

50
00:07:13,560 --> 00:07:18,365
And during that no sense of time, there's been no sense of self.

51
00:07:18,384 --> 00:07:20,548
So there's an absorption into the action.

52
00:07:21,829 --> 00:07:23,310
Sometimes you do it when you're reading.

53
00:07:23,670 --> 00:07:26,673
You do it easily when you're watching a film.

54
00:07:28,134 --> 00:07:29,016
No sense of time.

55
00:07:29,036 --> 00:07:33,120
You just wake up and it's two hours long, is it?

56
00:07:33,139 --> 00:07:36,502
Those moments when they actually...

57
00:07:38,254 --> 00:07:47,913
happen from the right understanding, with the right attitude, you see, when we go into that sort of experience, that's the enlightened mind.

58
00:07:50,216 --> 00:07:57,470
And we're in that peculiar paradox, that when we're completely happy like that, we don't know it.

59
00:07:59,954 --> 00:08:01,798
As soon as you know you're happy, you lost it.

60
00:08:02,807 --> 00:08:04,790
Because you know, I am happy.

61
00:08:04,831 --> 00:08:09,437
See, there's a split, there's a break between the happiness and you knowing that you're happy.

62
00:08:09,937 --> 00:08:15,625
And then, of course, you know it's going to end anyway, because everything arrives and passes away.

63
00:08:21,673 --> 00:08:28,562
Now, on the other side of the equation, that is that the negativity that we have

64
00:08:29,267 --> 00:08:34,975
which is sort of stored up from past behaviour, from past wrong thinking.

65
00:08:36,817 --> 00:08:45,849
So now, what we learn from our meditation is that you don't fight it, you don't try and get rid of it, you have to, as it were, accompany it.

66
00:08:46,870 --> 00:08:54,360
So, take our work, I would say it's impossible to do a job without sometimes feeling bored about it.

67
00:08:55,721 --> 00:08:58,245
So, where does that boredom come from, you see?

68
00:09:03,236 --> 00:09:06,341
Why does boredom arise?

69
00:09:08,524 --> 00:09:17,379
It's one of our big problems in this society because of the access to easy pleasure, easy entertainment, easy distraction.

70
00:09:18,721 --> 00:09:23,288
So when the mind is always seeking some sort of excitement,

71
00:09:23,639 --> 00:09:33,994
and you have to go back and do the same sort of work and say the same things day after day, and there isn't the excitement there, then what you get is this aversion, which is boredom.

72
00:09:36,197 --> 00:09:39,142
So then the boredom says to you, look, what you need is variety.

73
00:09:39,201 --> 00:09:41,725
Variety is the spice of life.

74
00:09:41,745 --> 00:09:45,731
So then you go seeking this variety, but it becomes a sort of,

75
00:09:47,652 --> 00:09:48,413
Obsession.

76
00:09:50,275 --> 00:09:53,741
An addiction to try and constantly find the next buzz.

77
00:09:58,109 --> 00:10:07,003
And the more you work at that, the more you find that you're more quickly bored by what you're doing.

78
00:10:08,125 --> 00:10:11,549
Because you can't keep that high level of excitement all the time.

79
00:10:15,832 --> 00:10:23,322
So when we find ourselves being bored about something, the answer to that is repetition.

80
00:10:23,722 --> 00:10:24,423
You keep doing it.

81
00:10:25,365 --> 00:10:32,714
You keep doing it knowing that the boredom is there and that it's coming from wrong understanding and you keep placing your attention on what you're doing.

82
00:10:33,995 --> 00:10:37,500
And then we find, magically, that the interest rises again.

83
00:10:37,679 --> 00:10:38,981
The commitment rises again.

84
00:10:40,903 --> 00:10:44,067
So now to undermine all this business around

85
00:10:45,111 --> 00:10:51,581
seeking excitement in life, is the quality of equanimity, calmness.

86
00:10:52,623 --> 00:10:57,229
And you'll notice that we always begin the meditation with that calmness.

87
00:10:58,630 --> 00:11:14,173
And it's really beginning to develop a taste for calmness, for the neutral, for a state of equanimity that begins to balance our lives, so that we're not always seeking this excitement, this distraction,

88
00:11:15,301 --> 00:11:17,543
And in a sense, that's our default position.

89
00:11:19,404 --> 00:11:42,490
If during daily life we can just, every so often, even if it's only for a few seconds, just fall back into that state of stopping, re-establish the calmness of the body, calmness of the mind, the stillness, silence of the mind, calmness of the heart, and then in that position,

90
00:11:42,993 --> 00:11:44,215
He wants to retain that.

91
00:11:44,235 --> 00:11:47,360
So as it were, open outwards.

92
00:11:47,379 --> 00:11:48,783
So it's a receptive mode.

93
00:11:49,003 --> 00:11:51,025
So we're not going out, we're receiving.

94
00:11:51,447 --> 00:11:52,589
And that's your equanimity.

95
00:11:55,933 --> 00:12:02,585
If that's your default position, you can see that anything which touches that equanimity is going to be interesting.

96
00:12:04,168 --> 00:12:09,777
Because you're not walking into the next moment with some preconception, some expectations.

97
00:12:11,477 --> 00:12:14,621
Some idea of attaining or getting or achieving.

98
00:12:20,448 --> 00:12:38,429
So in that default mode where they're just very calm, very still, very equanimous, we can repeat to ourselves that at this moment of being, not trying to become something, we're not achieving anything, going anywhere, not trying to be anybody.

99
00:12:41,701 --> 00:12:44,924
That's a relief, huh?

100
00:12:44,945 --> 00:12:45,986
That's a real holiday.

101
00:12:53,216 --> 00:13:05,092
And then, when the next thing to be done arises in the mind, the next thing to be done, wash the pots, make the intention, wash the pots.

102
00:13:05,113 --> 00:13:08,518
And when you wash the pots, your attention is on what you're doing.

103
00:13:09,798 --> 00:13:18,571
If you're speaking to somebody, your attention is on receiving what they're saying without trying to respond at the same time, which is what we normally do.

104
00:13:18,750 --> 00:13:21,294
We get into a sort of fencing.

105
00:13:23,217 --> 00:13:27,725
It's more important for them to understand what I mean rather than for me to understand what they mean.

106
00:13:28,485 --> 00:13:29,005
It's not important.

107
00:13:29,888 --> 00:13:36,817
So that receptive mode, and then there's a sort of change, there's sort of a click of...

108
00:13:39,312 --> 00:14:03,952
respond so all these little everything that we're doing in the sitting meditation has some relevance into daily life it's sort of the basic attitude in which we approach every moment in our lives

109
00:14:05,317 --> 00:14:11,285
And the effect is, you know, just a greater calmness, a bit more happiness around.

110
00:14:12,849 --> 00:14:13,669
Not so many enemies.

111
00:14:22,243 --> 00:14:26,370
So, just to sort of recap, we're not trying to be self-aware.

112
00:14:26,789 --> 00:14:29,754
In fact, we're trying to go to a point where we're not self-aware.

113
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:49,315
The guiding principles are paying attention and to do it with care, to put the heart into it, to make sure the intention that we are empowering is skillful, wholesome, and that we create during the day these moments of stillness.

114
00:14:49,436 --> 00:15:00,585
The more you create moments of stillness to establish that equanimity and move into the next moment, you'll see it has just the effect of calming our lives

115
00:15:04,091 --> 00:15:08,960
Just that moment allows us to make the right decision, you see.

116
00:15:10,903 --> 00:15:15,750
Don't get caught up in the old habits of greed, hatred, fear and delusion.

117
00:15:19,817 --> 00:15:22,883
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

118
00:15:22,903 --> 00:15:27,770
May you be liberated in this very lifetime, sooner rather than

